title: For Sale:  Browning Hi Power - Custom work by J. Garthwaite, Pistolsmith
postcontent:
Why do you want a Hi Power?
Because the Hi Power is one of the most reliable pistols in any configuration, and field-stripping and assembly are as simple as it gets. The Hi Power’s grip might also be the most ergonomic of any handgun. Slim, trim and just about the perfect weight for carry, the Hi Power is almost perfectly balanced, with the barrel and slide weighing within an ounce of the frame. This, with the grip, makes the Hi Power one of the easiest-shooting, easiest-to-control 9 mm pistols in the world.

Why do you want *this* Hi Power?
This is a TRUE Browning Hi Power, made in Belgium by FN Herstal. S/N starts with 245PV - 1986 manufacture. Jim Garthwaite, renowned Pistosmith, performed the custom work on this Hi Power, and all the papers, both Browning & Garthwaite, are with the pistol. Since the Garthwaite wait time exceeds one year now, this is the only way for a shooter wanting a Garthwaite BHP to have one today.

This work was done in 1999: Novak rear sight. Dovetail front sight. C&S hammer, trigger, trigger job with frame to slide fit. Remove mag safety. Strip pistol, complete radius, soften & deburr. Re-Parkerizing. 

The barrel was replaced in 2000. Fitted, crowned, and the front sight got it’s dot. It’s worn a Wolff 18.5 recoil spring & buffer since ’99. They’ve both been recently replaced. No time on the spring. Buyer will recieve all springs, buffer, stock grip panels, and two good magazines.

title: For Sale/Trade:  German Deutsche Werk Ortgies .32ACP W/Owner's Manual
postcontent:
Very good condition German made Ortgies 7.65mm (.32ACP). This gun is the commercial version, and the 6th variant (there were six model variants?). The Ortgies pocket pistols were made (officially) from 1919 to 1924. This particular gun (according to the serial number) was made around 1922-23. The Orgies semi-automatic pistols were excellent, well made guns. The design was ahead of its time. This gun has the factory original 7rd magazine. Overall, this gun is in very good condition. Has all matching numbers (barrel, frame, slide). Bluing is in really good condition for its age (this gun is at least 90 years old). All original finish, not re-blued, or anything like that. Has factory wood grips. The grips has no cracks, splits, or damages. Has a few minor dents and dings. Barrel is in very good condition - has a few minor surface rust. Bore is in very good condition. Has a a few minor rust (the Germans or people back in the old days used highly corrosive ammo). In addition, there's an old Ortgies owner's manual. It's really worn out, tattered, but all the pages are there (but not intact - it looks like as old as the gun itself). I took this gun as part of a package gun trade, and I like German made guns, however, I need to sell/trade this pistol to get a revolver for my wife for her CCW. She prefers a 38 Special snub nose revolver. You must be at least 21 years old or older and have a valid Kentucky driver's license (KY CCDW) to buy/trade this gun. Local (Kentucky) sale/trade only. No shipping. Just email me with any questions. Serious enquiries only please. Thanks for looking.

-- Below is an excerpt from one of the Ortgies websites. It is not my own. I am just giving a credit to the author/creator of that particular website. You can do a google (or yahoo) search on this particular pistol on the internet. There are several Ortgies websites on line --

" The Ortgies pistol has a number of unusual design features.  The most obvious is its grip safety which, once squeezed, stays in the “fire” position without further pressure of the hand on the grip.  A button on the left side of the gun allows the grip safety to pop back out.  Since the grip safety is powered by the striker spring, the safety can only be popped out, i.e., placed in the “safe” position, when the striker is cocked.  Hence, if the safety is enabled, the gun is cocked.  When the grip safety is enabled, the sear is prevented from moving downward and the tension on the striker spring is reduced.  Pressing the safety- enabling button also allows the slide to be lifted off the frame rail for disassembly.  The striker serves as the ejector. "

* $350 obo, or trade *

title: For Sale:  Winchester M1907 SLR Semi-Auto  20's "Gangster" Thompson style Carbine
postcontent:
This Unique Winchester Model 1907 Self Loading Rifle was manufactured in 1951. The 1907s were used in WWI by the Royal Flying Corps, French aviators (aerial observers) and by the US 1st Aero Squadron in support of General Pershing's troops in the Punitive Expedition. In the 1920's and 30's the M1907 was used by Police and Gangsters like Bonnie and Clyde and John Dillinger.
This particular rifle was the rare Police version with the larger mag release, front sling swivel and unique "finger grip" charging plunger. The non-Police versions have a round plunger end. You can see on the right side of the stock where the Police ID was removed.
The Rifle fires the powerful .351 Winchester round(still available on the internernet and through Buffaloarms.com. I have six or seven rounds with the rifle. It fires flawlessly from a factory 10 or two factory 5 round mags that come with the rifle.
To go along with this rifle's long history of Military, Police and Gangster use, I moded the rifle into a gangster carbine, as follows:
The Police identifiers on the stock were long ago removed, so I decided to create a Gangster version, which in fact actually existed. I skifully removed 2" of the stock, which was ridiculously long from the factory! I removed three inches from the 19" barrel, professionally threaded and crowned it and added a Thompson muzzle compensator.
I then had a special forend made so that I could introduce a Thompson foregrip inside the forend. I matched the forend with the stock perfectly!. The grip, does not match perfectly by design...they never did or would match as they were a Gangster mod. Has a period Thompson canvas sling.  The overall length is 35". The original bluing is about 98% and is much brighter than my pics indicate. Where it looks worn is glare. This gun will make a great Gangster Wars period showpiece or re-enactor gun. It fires like the day it was made! It is a Beast! The .351 is equivilent to a .357 mag. ballistically. 
Please e-mail any questions: REDACTED ot text Joe at 614 five 5 four seven 9 2 four.
Would do a partial trade for a nice pistol or MAKE CASH OFFER! Thanks, Joe

NOTE: Not Extar. Mfg. or 300 Blackout...it will not go away!
